    <item>
      <title>Projects</title>
      <link>https://awlfleck.github.io/projects/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://awlfleck.github.io/projects/</guid>
      <description>&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;estimation-and-management-of-stable-distributed-risk&#34;&gt;&#xA;  Estimation and Management of Stable-distributed Risk:&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;heading-link&#34; href=&#34;#estimation-and-management-of-stable-distributed-risk&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &lt;i class=&#34;fa-solid fa-link&#34; aria-hidden=&#34;true&#34; title=&#34;Link to heading&#34;&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&#xA;    &lt;span class=&#34;sr-only&#34;&gt;Link to heading&lt;/span&gt;&#xA;  &lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The lion&amp;rsquo;s share of my PhD research was concerned with how to model, estimate and manage risk modeled by &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stable_distribution&#34;  class=&#34;external-link&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;Stable distributions&lt;/a&gt;. I was particularly concerned with the case of jointly distributed idiosyncratic and systematic risk (think the CAPM or delta hedging). Stables as a family of distributions are quite beautiful and elegant and have many desirable properties for risk modeling but they lack closed form pdfs and can be challenging to handle computationally. My goal in these papers was to bridge the gap between theory and application.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Teaching Experience</title>
