      <description>&lt;p&gt;In a previous life&lt;!--(Winters &#39;21 &amp; &#39;23)--&gt; I was the course director and instructor respectively at York University for:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;h3 id=&#34;math-4281-ruin-theory-and-credibility&#34;&gt;&#xA;  Math 4281: Ruin Theory and Credibility&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;heading-link&#34; href=&#34;#math-4281-ruin-theory-and-credibility&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &lt;i class=&#34;fa-solid fa-link&#34; aria-hidden=&#34;true&#34; title=&#34;Link to heading&#34;&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&#xA;    &lt;span class=&#34;sr-only&#34;&gt;Link to heading&lt;/span&gt;&#xA;  &lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h3&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;This was a 4th year undergraduate class for actuarial science students and was considered adequate preparation for exam C of the Society of Actuaries (SOA). My understanding is that the ruin theory component has be phased out, which is unfortunate given how foundational is is.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
